          ease-[cubic-bezier(0.165,0.85,0.45,1)] h-8 w-8 rounded-md _fill_10ocf_9 _ghost_10ocf_96" type="button" aria-label="View request/response" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 256 256" class="text-text-300"><path d="M69.12,94.15,28.5,128l40.62,33.85a8,8,0,1,1-10.24,12.29l-48-40a8,8,0,0,1,0-12.29l48-40a8,8,0,0,1,10.24,12.3Zm176,27.7-48-40a8,8,0,1,0-10.24,12.3L227.5,128l-40.62,33.85a8,8,0,1,0,10.24,12.29l48-40a8,8,0,0,0,0-12.29ZM162.73,32.48a8,8,0,0,0-10.25,4.79l-64,176a8,8,0,0,0,4.79,10.26A8.14,8.14,0,0,0,96,224a8,8,0,0,0,7.52-5.27l64-176A8,8,0,0,0,162.73,32.48Z"></path></svg></button></div></div><div id="mcp-app-placeholder-toolu_01AAPHLefBtSfpY4Ev6reDPk" class="w-full" style="height: 0px;"></div><div id="mcp-app-container-toolu_01AAPHLefBtSfpY4Ev6reDPk" class="w-full" style=""><div class="h-full w-full"><iframe title="visualize: Zarik memory structure" sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-forms" allow="fullscreen *; clipboard-write *" src="./zarik_files/mcp_apps(1).html" style="width: 100%; border-width: medium; border-style: none; border-color: currentcolor; border-image: initial; background-color: transparent; height: 720px;"></iframe></div></div></div><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Here's how the memory flows through the agent:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Load</strong> — when a user sends <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">/start</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">load_memory(telegram_id)</code> checks <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">data/memory/{telegram_id}.json</code>. If the file exists, it returns the full memory dict. If not, it creates a fresh skeleton with empty preferences and no past trips.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Read</strong> — the <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">greet_node</code> checks <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">past_itineraries</code>. If there are entries, it passes the full memory JSON into the greeting prompt so the LLM can say things like "Welcome back! Last time you explored Japan for 7 days." The memory dict also gets stored in <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">AgentState["user_memory"]</code> so other nodes can reference it during the conversation.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Update</strong> — after <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">generate_node</code> produces an itinerary, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">update_memory_from_trip()</code> does four things: appends the new destination to <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">preferred_destinations</code> (deduped), updates <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">budget_range</code>, <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">group_size_typical</code>, and <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">dietary</code> from the current trip's preferences, builds a new itinerary entry with destination/dates/days/timestamp, and trims to the last 10 entries.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Save</strong> — <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">save_memory()</code> stamps <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">last_seen</code> with the current timestamp and writes the dict back to the JSON file with pretty-printing.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The ClawdBot-style pattern here is that it's file-based, per-user, and accumulates over time rather than being a fixed profile. Each trip enriches the memory, so the 5th conversation is noticeably more personalized than the first. Click any node in the diagram to dig into the specific code.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
