]:border-0.5 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-border-400 [&amp;_.ignore-pre-bg&gt;div]:bg-transparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8"><div><div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown"><p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">No no — you're still using Telegram. "Webhook mode" is just a different way Telegram delivers messages to your bot. Right now you're using <strong>polling mode</strong> — your bot keeps asking Telegram "any new messages?" every few seconds. <strong>Webhook mode</strong> means Telegram pushes messages to your server instantly when they arrive.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Think of it like this:</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Polling (current):</strong> Your bot calls Telegram 24/7 saying "anything new? anything new? anything new?" — wastes resources, slower, and causes the 409 conflict issues you saw when two instances run.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]"><strong>Webhook (enterprise):</strong> You give Telegram a URL like <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">https://zarik.yourdomain.com/webhook</code>, and Telegram sends messages directly to that URL the instant a user types something — faster, no conflicts, less resource usage.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Both still use Telegram. Same bot, same user experience. Just a different delivery method under the hood.</p>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">The full enterprise upgrade I mentioned would be:</p>
<ul class="[li_&amp;]:mb-0 [li_&amp;]:mt-1 [li_&amp;]:gap-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ul]:pb-1 [&amp;:not(:last-child)_ol]:pb-1 list-disc flex flex-col gap-1 pl-8 mb-3">
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Webhook mode</strong> → Telegram pushes to your FastAPI endpoint (needs HTTPS, which Railway gives you free)</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Rate limiting</strong> → stop users from spamming 100 messages per second and burning your Groq credits</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Input sanitization</strong> → clean user messages before they hit the LLM</li>
<li class="whitespace-normal break-words pl-2"><strong>Docker Compose</strong> → one <code class="bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]">docker-compose up</code> spins up bot + API + Postgres + Redis together</li>
</ul>
<p class="font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal leading-[1.7]">Want me to implement these upgrades?</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-start opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 group-focus-within:opacity-100 transition" role="group" aria-label="Message actions"><div class="text-text-300"><div class="text-text-300 flex items-stretch justify-between"><div class="w-fit" data-state="closed"><button class="inline-flex
